\subsection{Unification}

Rules \rulename{ucon} and \rulename{utup} do conventional unification, decomposing
tuples where necessary.  Notice that |e_1 == e_2| reduces to its unified value.  For example,
|(3==3) + 7| reduces to |10|.

In rule \rulename{ucon} there are two uses of ``$=$'', but they are different!  The ``|k_1 == k_2|''
on the LHS is part of the syntax of Verse. In contrast
the ``$k_1 = k_2$'' in the side-condition is ``real'' equality: it means that |k_1| and |k_2| are the
same constant.

\paragraph{Substitution}

Once we have an equality that indicates that a variable must be equal to a given value here, we can use rule \rulename{subst} to propagate that information in the surrounding context. Note that the substitution applies to the \emph{context} |X|, with a hole where the equation |x = v| was, and we put the equation |x = v| back into the hole afterwards.

The first side-condition $x \in \freevars{X}$ merely prevents this rule from firing vacuously. The second side-condition $x\notin \freevars{v}$, also called the “occurs check”, prevents recursive values from propagating.

We can use this rule even far away from where the variable |x| is defined. For example, an equation |x=1| in the condition of an |if| does not define |x|, but we may still use that equation within the condition of the |if|:
\[
\begin{array}{ll}
& |def x ((if x = 1; x > 2 then e1 else e2); dots)| \\
\movesto & |def x ((if x = 1; 1 > 2 then e1 else e2); dots)| \\
\movesto^\ast & |def x ((if fail then e1 else e2); dots)| \\
\movesto & |def x (e2; dots)|
\end{array}
\]

The context |X| crucially prevents us from using the equation for |x| where it does not hold; we cannot rewrite |(x = 1) choice (x + 2)| to |(x = 1) choice (1 + 2)|.


Once all occurrences of a variable |x| have been substituted this way, we can remove its bindings with rule \rulename{def-unused}. This rule only removes variables that have a definition. It is illegal in Verse to introduce a variable and never assign it a value, as in |def x 1|.


Rule \rulename{swap} swaps |(e=x)| to |(x=e)| to allow rule \rulename{subst} to fire.
We just need to be careful that we cannot swap |(x=y)| to |(y=x)| and back forever; hence the side condition.

\paragraph{Recursion}

The side condition $x \notin \freevars{v}$ in rule \rulename{subst} ensures that |v| does not mention |x| itself -- the ``occurs check''. This way we cannot use cyclic values like |x = (x,x)|.

Verse supports recursive functions and closures, such as |loop = (y => applyx loop y)|. This equation cannot be used by \rulename{subst} directly, due the occurs check. Therefore \rulename{subst-rec} will push the binding inside the lambda and rewrite to |loop = (y => def loop (loop = (y => applyx loop y); apply loop y))|. Now |loop| is no longer a free variable of the value on the right hand side and \rulename{subst} can fire. This rule appears to be looping, but applying rules under a lambda is generally at risk of looping. It also works if the recursive lambda is nested more deeply, as in |loops = ((y => applyx(applyx loops 1)y), (y => applyx(applyx loops 0)y))|.

\paragraph{Scope expansion}

Rule \rulename{def-float} expands the scope of variables within the current execution context $X$, and \rulename{def-merge} combines all variables with the same scope in a single |defKW|, to allow |subst| to fire more easily.For example in
    $$ |def x  (dots x dots(def z (dots(x==(3,z))dots))dots)| $$
it would be dangerous if \rulename{subst} could substitute |(3,z)| for |x| right away, because |z| is not in scope everywhere where |x| is. But after floating and merging we get
    $$ |def (x,z)  (dots x dots(dots(x==(3,z))dots)dots)| $$
and now we can safely invoke \rulename{subst} on |x == (3,z)|.

\paragraph{Reflexivity}

One might expect to see the innocent looking rule \rulename{uvar} allowing $|x == x| \movesto |x|$, but such a rule would lead to non-confluence. Consider |def x (x = (y => y); (x == x))|. If we use \rulename{subst} first, we will then unify two lambda values, which reduces to |wrong| per \rulename{unify-wrong}, but if we use \rulename{uvar} first, the term would reduce to |(y => y)|.

\subsection{Choice and failure}

Rule \rulename{choose} is the crucial one: it duplicates an entire expression with a nested choice, moving that expression into the choice, where we then can make more progress:
$$|def x (x == (1 choice 2))| \movesto |def x (x == 1) `choice` def x (x == 2)|$$

Two aspects of this rule deserve explanation:
\begin{enumerate}
\item Note the use of the \emph{choice-free} context |CX|!  For example, the
expression
$$
|def (x,y) ((x == (3 choice 4)) ; (y == (9 choice 2)); (x,y))|
$$
should yield the values |(3,9)|, |(3,2)|, |(4,9)|, |(4,2)|, in that order.
To get the order right, we must apply \rulename{choose} to the first choice |(3 choice 4)| first, and only
then to the second |(9 choice 2)|.  This is achieved by using |CX| in \rulename{choose} to ensure that only the
\emph{leftmost} choice can be chosen.

Because we need to expand choices in the right order, we are stuck with a program like the following:
$$ |def (x,y) (y = applyx x (); x = ((_ => (1 choice 2)) choice (_ => (3 choice 4 choice 5)));y)| $$
We cannot expand the choice, because |applyx x ()| is not choice-free, but we cannot make progress there either, because we need to know the value of |x|.

\item The |SX| context anchors the rule at a \emph{choice-limiting construct}, such as choice itself.

This is important to avoid getting stuck. Without this provision, rule \rulename{choose} would allow the following transition:
$$
\begin{array}{rl}
&|def x (applyx x (); x = (_ => (1 choice 2)); (3 choice 4))| \\ \movesto  &  |def x (applyx x (); ((x = (_ => (1 choice 2)); 3)choice(x = (_ => (1 choice 2)); 4)))|
\end{array}
$$
This is bad, because now the equation that we can use to define |x| using \rulename{subst} is no longer visible to \rulename{subst}, as the |X| context does not reach into choices, and we are suddently stuck.


Note that in examples, we often treat the whole expression as if it was in an |SX| context.
\end{enumerate}


The rules listed under \emph{Fail propagation} collapse expressions with a nested |fail| into a single |fail|.


\subsection{Functions and application}

Rule \rulename{app-lam} is our jolly simple $\beta$-reduction rule. Since our grammar requires function applications to always have a \emph{value} as the argument, the duplication performed by substitution does not risk duplicating work or effects. But note that that we \emph{can} apply this rule even when the argument is a yet unknown variable.

A tuples/array behaves like a (finite) function, and can be applied to a numeric value
in \rulename{app-arr} to index it: |applyx (array (v_0,dots v_n)) k| evaluates to |v_k| if |k| is a number within the bounds of the array, or to |fail| otherwise. But since \rulename{app-arr} is defined via choice, the expression |y = applyx a x| actually enumerates the positions and values of all entries of the array |a|. For example, |all (def x (42 = applyx a x; x))| finds the indicies of all entries in |a| that are 42. Note that an application of the empty array |applyx (array ()) v| always fails, even if |v| is not a number.


\subsection{Conditionals}

In Verse, an |if|-expression does not evaluate its condition to a Boolean true or false.  Instead
it tests whether its condition succeeds (i.e. returns one or more values) or fails (returning no values). The essence of this check is captured in the |one e| construct, which evaluates to the \emph{first} value returned by |e|. The conventional |if e_1 then e_2 else e_3| construct can be built on top of |oneKW|.

For example |if (x=3) then e_1 else e_2| tries to unify |x| and |3|; if that succeeds (returning one value, namely |3|)
the |if| returns |e_1|, otherwise it returns |e_2|.

Comparision operators succeed or fail, rather than returning a Boolean
(as in most languages). For example |(x>3)| succeeds if |x| is greater
than 3, returning |x|; and fails if not.

It is very important that in |one ((x=3;1) choice 2)| we
treat |x| as ``rigid'': the conditional is intended to \emph{test}
|x|'s value, rather \emph{giving} |x| its value!  That is why rule \rulename{subst}
does not look inside an |oneKW| (look at the syntax of context |X| used in that rule).

\subsection{|wrong| and the verifier}
Some expressions don't make sense, such as using a number as a function in function application, or comparing two lambda values. These expressions are wrong in a different way than failing expressions and stuck expressions:
\begin{itemize}
\item The expression |(1=2)|, for example in an |if| conditional, is benign and its reduction to |fail| is part of the normal course of program execution.
\item The expression |def x (applyx (one (x = 1; (y => (x = 1)))) ())| (with implicit ANFing) is stuck, as no rule can make progress, but there is nothing obivously wrong with this program.
\end{itemize}

To clearly identify wrong terms, we introduce the special construct |wrong| to the syntax, and rewrite bad expressions to |wrong| using the rules in Figure \ref{fig:wrong-axioms}. Programs go wrong if they
\begin{itemize}
\item Add or compare values that are not numbers
\item Use numbers as functions
\item Unify lambdas
\item Fail the occurs check, as in |x = (1,x)|
\item Fail effect annotations (|succeedsKW|, |decidesKW|)
\end{itemize}

The introduction of |wrong| is crucial to give a specification to a \emph{verifier}, which is a static analysis that rules out the existence of a wrong reduction; according to the motto “verified programs don’t go wrong”.

But not every |wrong| is wrong: because we allow reduction everywhere, even in eventually unused code, we must allow for |wrong| to appear temporarily, as in this reduction:
\[
|one (1 choice (applyx 2 3))| \movesto |one (1 choice wrong)| \movesto |1|
\]

Only those occurrences of |wrong| that are “needed” matter. To identify those, we can extend our reduction semantics with the |wrong| propagation rules in Figure~\ref{fig:wrong-propagation}. With these in place, the verifier will guarantee that the overall program does not evaluate to |wrong|, even though subexpressions may be |wrong|. Therefore, the propagation rules are irrelevant for the execution of verified program.

Note that the rule propagation rules for |wrong| can compete with fail propagation rules. This is ok: The specification of the verifier forbids the existene of \emph{any} bad reduction sequence.

\subsection{Source Verse}

In the Verse source language we do not write explicit |defKW|s. Instead, they are added
by a simple preprocessing step, that introduces a variable |x| in the innermost
|defKW| that encloses all its uses.
\simon{It's hard to say more until we say more about Source Verse.}

In the arms of a choice |(e_1 choice e_2)| we add a |def h e_1| around |e_1| if
|e_1| introduces any new variables; and similarly |e_2|.
