\section{Confluence}

We aspire our reduction rules to be confluent: For every expression $e$, if $e \movesto^\ast e_1$ and $e \movesto^\ast e_2$, then there exists $e_3$ such that $e_1 \movesto^\ast e_3$ and $e_2 \movesto^\ast e_3$. Note that $e$ can be an open term.

Confluence allows us to apply the rules anywhere, in arbitrary order, without running into a dead end.

\subsection{Confluence and convertibility}

A confluent relation has the Church-Rosser-Property: If $e_1 \convertible e_2$, then there exists $e_3$ such that $e_1 \movesto^\ast e_3$ and $e_2 \movesto^\ast e_3$. Put different: We can follow the reduction relation forwards and backwards, and must still be able to join the terms.

This allows us to discover rules that we need to add to our reduction relation to make it confluent. These rules are not reqiured for evaluation.

\subsection{Associativity of sequencing}

In the following we assume the
\[ \rulename{seq-assoc} \quad |(e1; e2); e3| \movesto |e1; (e2; e3)| \]
to simplify reasoning about sequences without worrying about how they nest.

\subsection{Order of variables in |defKW|}

The rules \rulename{def-float} and \rulename{def-merge} can easily lead to superficial non-confluence where terms differ in the order variables occr in a |defKW|. We hand-wave that problem away by equating terms up to alpha-equivalence where the list of variables in |defKW| is considered a \emph{set} of bound variables.

\subsection{Swap-seq-val}

A slightly technical rule, but we want to use it later: because of
\begin{conteq}
           |(v_1 = v_2; v_1)| \\
\movesfrom |def z (z = v_2; z = v_1)|
\movesto   |v_2; v_2 = v_1|
\movesto   |v_2 = v_1|
\end{conteq}
we want the rule
\[ \rulename{swap-seq-val} \quad |(v_1 = v_2);v_1| \movesto |(v_2 = v_1)| \]

\subsection{Local substitution}

The (local) substitution rule \rulename{subst} was strongly motivated by our desire to have a confluent system. Previously, we had a single rule that combined \rulename{subst} and \rulename{def-unused}, and thus only fired when the definig equality was within reach of the |defKW|. But that was not confluent:

Consider the following chain of reductions, where |C| denotes an arbitrary context:
\begin{conteq}
             |x = v; C^[x]|    \\
\movesfrom   |x; x = v; C^[x]| \\
\movesfrom   |def y (y = x; y = v; C^[y])| \\
\movesto     |v = x; v; C[v]| \\
\movesfrom   |(v = x; v); C[v]| \\
\movesto     |x = v; C[v]| \\
\end{conteq}

% A possible formulation of this could be
% 
% \[ \rulename{subst} \quad |C^[x]| \movesto |C^[v]| \text{ if } |C^[x]| = |X^[x = v]|, |C^[hole]| \ne |X^[hole = v]| \]
% 
% which we can unpack as follows:
% \begin{itemize}
% \item The rule replaces a \emph{single} occurrence of |x| to |v|, anywhere within the current expression |C[x]|. This uses a (not yet spelled out) context |C| that reaches everywhere within an expression, even under lambdas etc.
% \item Of course this is only ok if we may assume that |x| is equal to |v| within the current expression. This is the case if the equation |x=v| is part of the current expression, but not hidden under a lambda or similar; this is what the |X| context says. The first side conditions says that “the current expression |C[x]| has |x=v| within the reach of the execution context |X|.
% \item The occurence of |x| that we replace must \emph{not} be the one in the equation |x = v|; we certainly do not want to rewrite |x = 1| to |1 = 1|. The second side conditions ensures that.
% \item There is no side condition $x \notin \freevars{v}$. The chain of reductions above that justify this rule work even when $x \in \freevars{v}$. This means that an equation |x = (x,x)| can be used for local rewriting over and over, but that seems to be ok.
% \end{itemize}

There is no requirement $x \notin v$ in that derivation. We still restrict \rulename{subst} that way, and use \rulename{occurs-check} to handle programs that have equations like |x = (1,x)|.

Note that the chain of reduction above actually also works if instead of $x$ we have any value. This yields
\[
v_1 = v_2; |C^[v_1]| \convertible |v_1 = v_2; C^[v_2]|
\]
We do not need to add that as a separate rule, by the following case anaysis:
\begin{itemize}
\item If |v_1| is a variable, \rulename{subst} applies.
\item If |v_1| is not a variable, but |v_2| is, \rulename{swap} allows us to use \rulename{subst}.
\item If |v_1| and |v_2| are both constants and the same, substitution would not have any effect.
\item If |v_1| and |v_2| are both arrays of the same length, rule \rulename{uarr} decomposes it into equalities between the components. Substitution of the whole array can now be performed by substitution using the component equalities.
\item If |v_1| and |v_2| are different constants, tuples of different lengths or else inconsistent, it evaluates to |fail| or |wrong|, and that swallows the whole contex that could be affected by first substituting.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Handling |wrong| terms}

Dealing with |wrong| is a challenge when trying to define a confluent semantics.
In particular: should |wrong;fail| reduce to |wrong| or to |fail|?

On the one hand, we have
\begin{conteq}
           |wrong| \\
\movesfrom |wrong; 1| \\
\movesfrom |wrong; (1 = 1)| \\
\movesfrom |(_ => 1) = (_ => 2); applyx (_ => 1) () = 1| \\
\movesfrom |def x (x = (_ => 1); x = (_ => 2); applyx x() = 1| \\
\movesto   |(_ => 2) = (_ => 1); applyx (_ => 2) () = 1| \\
\movesto   |wrong; (2 = 1)| \\
\movesto   |wrong;fail|
\end{conteq}
which calls for $|wrong;fail| \movesto |wrong|$. On the other hand we have
\begin{conteq}
           |fail| \\
\movesfrom |fail; fail| \\
\movesfrom |fail; if fail then wrong else fail| \\
\movesfrom |(1 = 2); if 1 = 2 then wrong else fail| \\
\movesfrom |def x (x = 1; x = 2; if x = 2 then wrong else fail)| \\
\movesto   |(2 = 1); if 2 = 2 then wrong else fail)| \\
\movesto   |fail; wrong|
\end{conteq}
calling for $|wrong;fail| \movesto |fail|$.

In both cases, we have inconsistent information in the present equation, and using that inconsistent informaion we can get different results. To achieve confluence, we have to fail uniformly in the presence of inconsistent information, and thus we add the rule
\[ \rulename{wrong-is-fail} \quad |wrong| \movesto |fail| \]
to treat them the same.

Of course, the |wrong| propagation rules in Figure~\ref{fig:wrong-propagation} must not be used, this would clearly be not confluent. That is ok, though, as these rules are relevant for specifying the verifier. If the verifier is sound, then verified programs can be reduced without these rules.

\subsection{Confluence proof}

With all these rules above added, and maybe some more to take care of minor syntactic differences (order of variable bindings), are the reduction rules confluent? \joachim{I don’t know yet, and I am unsure how to prove it.}

A proof sketch would argue that using \rulename{subst} and decomposition of equalities, we can exhaustively propagate all available information about free variables, and after this propagation, convertible terms are equal.


